Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE I/O - Convenience Wrappers Over io_core File Operations
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Higher-level file I/O primitives layered on top of io_core. The io_core
Note: module exposes raw handles and byte buffers; this module exposes the
Note: idiomatic "read whole file as string" / "write string to file" /
Note: "append" / "line iteration" calls that the rest of the compiler reaches
Note: for. Built on direct Linux syscalls (read=0, write=1, open=2, close=3)
Note: through the existing runtime entry points.

Note: Conventions:
Note:   - Path arguments are null-terminated C strings (Integer pointers).
Note:   - Return type Integer for content reads holds a pointer to a
Note:     null-terminated heap-allocated buffer; caller takes ownership.
Note:   - All write operations return bytes-written on success or a negative
Note:     errno value on failure.
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: OPEN MODE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Mirror the POSIX O_* flags used by the open(2) syscall. Combine with
Note: bitwise OR for compound modes (e.g. write_create_truncate).

Constant FILE_MODE_READ_ONLY as Integer is 0
Constant FILE_MODE_WRITE_ONLY as Integer is 1
Constant FILE_MODE_READ_WRITE as Integer is 2
Constant FILE_MODE_CREATE as Integer is 64
Constant FILE_MODE_EXCLUSIVE as Integer is 128
Constant FILE_MODE_TRUNCATE as Integer is 512
Constant FILE_MODE_APPEND as Integer is 1024

Note: Default permissions for newly-created files (0644 - owner read+write,
Note: group/other read-only).
Constant FILE_DEFAULT_PERMS as Integer is 420

Note: Maximum file size accepted by read_entire_file. Files larger than this
Note: are rejected to prevent unbounded memory allocation during compiler runs.
Constant FILE_MAX_SIZE as Integer is 134217728

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SYSCALL WRAPPERS
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Direct Linux x86_64 syscall numbers. Other platforms route through the
Note: runtime's syscall dispatcher (see runtime.c).

Process called "fio_syscall0" takes syscall_num as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Zero-argument syscall (close, etc.)
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "fio_syscall1" takes syscall_num as Integer, arg1 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: One-argument syscall - dispatched by the runtime.
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "fio_syscall3" takes syscall_num as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Three-argument syscall (read/write/open).
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BASIC FILE OPERATIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Open a file by path with the given combined mode flags. Returns the file
Note: descriptor on success, or a negative errno on failure.
Note: For read-only access prefer open_read; for fresh writes prefer
Note: open_write_truncate; for log-style writes prefer open_append.
Process called "fio_open" takes path as Integer, flags as Integer, perms as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: syscall 2 = open on x86_64 Linux. The runtime dispatches by number.
    Let fd be fio_syscall3(2, path, flags, perms)
    Return fd
End Process

Note: Open for reading. Fails (negative return) if the path doesn't exist.
Process called "fio_open_read" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Return fio_open(path, FILE_MODE_READ_ONLY, 0)
End Process

Note: Open for writing, creating the file if missing and truncating to zero
Note: length if it exists. Permissions default to 0644.
Process called "fio_open_write_truncate" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Let flags be FILE_MODE_WRITE_ONLY plus FILE_MODE_CREATE
    Set flags to flags plus FILE_MODE_TRUNCATE
    Return fio_open(path, flags, FILE_DEFAULT_PERMS)
End Process

Note: Open for appending. Creates the file if missing. Writes always land
Note: at end-of-file regardless of seek position.
Process called "fio_open_append" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Let flags be FILE_MODE_WRITE_ONLY plus FILE_MODE_CREATE
    Set flags to flags plus FILE_MODE_APPEND
    Return fio_open(path, flags, FILE_DEFAULT_PERMS)
End Process

Note: Close a previously-opened file descriptor. Returns 0 on success.
Process called "fio_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Return fio_syscall1(3, fd)
End Process

Note: Read up to count bytes from fd into buffer. Returns bytes actually read
Note: (0 = EOF, negative = error).
Process called "fio_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Return fio_syscall3(0, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Note: Write count bytes from buffer to fd. Returns bytes actually written.
Note: Short writes are possible - callers should loop until count is fully
Note: written or an error is reported.
Process called "fio_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Return fio_syscall3(1, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Note: Reposition the file offset. whence: 0 = SEEK_SET, 1 = SEEK_CUR, 2 = SEEK_END.
Process called "fio_seek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Return fio_syscall3(8, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

Note: Return current file length by seeking to end and back to start.
Note: Returns -1 on error.
Process called "fio_file_length" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Let length be fio_seek(fd, 0, 2)
    If length is less than 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let restore be fio_seek(fd, 0, 0)
    If restore is less than 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Return length
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIGH-LEVEL CONVENIENCE WRAPPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Read the entire contents of a file as a null-terminated string. Allocates
Note: a fresh buffer sized to file length + 1. Returns 0 on error.
Note: Caller takes ownership of the returned buffer.
Process called "read_entire_file" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fd be fio_open_read(path)
    If fd is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let length be fio_file_length(fd)
    If length is less than 0:
        Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is greater than FILE_MAX_SIZE:
        Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc memory_allocate from MemoryCore with length plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let total_read be 0
    Let remaining be length
    While remaining is greater than 0:
        Let chunk be fio_read(fd, buffer plus total_read, remaining)
        If chunk is less than 0:
            proc memory_free from MemoryCore with buffer
            Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
            Return 0
        End If
        If chunk is equal to 0:
            Set remaining to 0
        Otherwise:
            Set total_read to total_read plus chunk
            Set remaining to remaining minus chunk
        End If
    End While

    Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
    Note: null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with buffer, total_read, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: Write content (a null-terminated string) to path, replacing any existing
Note: contents. Creates the file if missing. Returns bytes written on success,
Note: or a negative value on failure.
Process called "write_entire_file" takes path as Integer, content as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fd be fio_open_write_truncate(path)
    If fd is less than 0:
        Return fd
    End If

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with content
    Let total_written be 0
    While total_written is less than length:
        Let remaining be length minus total_written
        Let chunk be fio_write(fd, content plus total_written, remaining)
        If chunk is less than 0:
            Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
            Return chunk
        End If
        If chunk is equal to 0:
            Set total_written to length
        Otherwise:
            Set total_written to total_written plus chunk
        End If
    End While

    Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
    Return total_written
End Process

Note: Append content to the end of path. Creates the file if missing.
Note: Returns bytes written.
Process called "append_to_file" takes path as Integer, content as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fd be fio_open_append(path)
    If fd is less than 0:
        Return fd
    End If

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with content
    Let total_written be 0
    While total_written is less than length:
        Let remaining be length minus total_written
        Let chunk be fio_write(fd, content plus total_written, remaining)
        If chunk is less than 0:
            Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
            Return chunk
        End If
        If chunk is equal to 0:
            Set total_written to length
        Otherwise:
            Set total_written to total_written plus chunk
        End If
    End While

    Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
    Return total_written
End Process

Note: True (1) if the path can be opened for reading.
Process called "file_readable" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fd be fio_open_read(path)
    If fd is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LINE-ORIENTED HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Locate the byte offset of the next newline (0x0A) starting from offset
Note: in buffer of total length len. Returns the offset of the newline, or
Note: len if no newline is found.
Process called "find_next_newline" takes buffer as Integer, offset as Integer, len as Integer returns Integer:
    Let i be offset
    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with buffer, i
        If ch is equal to 10:
            Return i
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return len
End Process

Note: Count the number of lines in a string (newline-terminated regions). A
Note: file with no trailing newline still counts the trailing fragment.
Process called "count_lines" takes content as Integer returns Integer:
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with content
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with content, i
        If ch is equal to 10:
            Note: Don't count trailing newline as a separate empty line.
            If i is less than length minus 1:
                Set count to count plus 1
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return count
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PATH UTILITIES
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Return 1 if path begins with '/' (absolute Unix path) or 'X:' (Windows).
Process called "is_absolute_path" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    If path is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let first be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with path, 0
    If first is equal to 47:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: Windows drive letter form like "C:\..."
    Let second be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with path, 1
    If second is equal to 58:
        If first is greater than or equal to 65:
            If first is less than or equal to 90:
                Return 1
            End If
            If first is greater than or equal to 97:
                If first is less than or equal to 122:
                    Return 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: Find the byte offset of the last directory separator ('/' or '\') in
Note: path. Returns -1 if no separator is present.
Process called "last_separator_offset" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with path
    Let last be 0 minus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with path, i
        If ch is equal to 47:
            Set last to i
        End If
        If ch is equal to 92:
            Set last to i
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return last
End Process
